default3. Why do numbers of women in STEM academic car
defaulteers decline further up the career ladder?
default3.1 
defaultBalancing a family with a work life is seen as the
default biggest cause of this decline.
default 
default 
defaultS
defaultome women 
defaulthave no choice but
default to permanently leave to bring up their families.
default  T
defaulthere are often fewer opportunities for STEM 
defaultjobs to be carried out as part-time roles and/or to allow flexible working arrangement for those women who want to return after maternity leave.
default This was perceived to be more of a factor in academia than in the public of private sector where the metrics us
defaulted to judge success in academia are challenging.  Being less able to travel for work because of family commitments can seri
defaultously hamper career progression. This is particularly relevant in
default marine science when scientific research cruises may be days, weeks 
defaultor even months in duration.  Presenting at conferences
default (normally overseas)
default and working in collaborative projects are near impossible 
defaultfor women with young children 
defaultand opportunities for informal networking with peers are missed. Senior academics and manager
defaults want to be able to send their staff to events to raise their organisation’s profile and will be reluctant to employ women who can’t travel for extended periods. 
default In addition, the 
defaulttemporary/short term funding model for research gives very little security,
default which is, again, non-conducive to starting a family. 
defaultWith the focus on high output of high-quality journal papers as the measure of success (of individuals and universities) this also puts extra pressure on women who take time out for family commitments.
default3.2 
defaultThe culture of academia was questioned and those members who worked in academia, particularly overseas, reported that most senior academics are seen to work evenings and weekends and most would not take anywhere near their annual leave allowance.  For 
defaultwoman who have, or are wanting to have a family
default, 
defaultthis culture makes it extremely difficult to stay in academia. 
default 
default3.3 
defaultMembers commented that 
defaultthe academic environment is often aggressive, without offering compensation in terms of job satisfaction. There is 
defaulta general belief that individuals are working against one another and constructive criticism can be harsh and a demonstration of ‘one-upmanship’. This contributes to a feeling that part time working and parental leave is frowned upon and will compromise a 
defaultwoman’s career.
default3.4 
defaultThe hierarchy is very male dominated and perceived as unsympathetic to young females entering academia.  There is a lack of female role models. On the occasions when female supervisors were experienced, it did not seem that these women 
defaultwere particularly interested in supporting other women in STEM, giving the i
defaultmpression that incoming female students and post-docs were a threat, and treating them with hostility
default. In many cases men were seen as better role models within academia. However, t
defaulthere is a lack of mentoring 
defaultlevel
default for women
default that men typically receive, both formally and informally. This may be because there is some stigma against senior men associating with junior women (either real or perceived).
default3.5 
defaultS
defaulttatistically, successful women 
defaultare more like to be in a dual career couple, and the challenges inherent within this are more likely to result in the woman rather than the man tailoring back their work
default with mothers normally the primary care giver
default. Correspondence in Nature (
defaulthttp://www.nature.com/ngeo/journal/v4/n4/pdf/ngeo1113.pdf
default) supports this 
defaultwithin the field of 
defaultphysical oceanography, where the women to men ratio 
defaultis decreased
default higher up the academic ladder
default in the U
defaultS
default. What is most worrying is that the 
defaultwomen/male ratio
default has decrease
defaultd
default in the last
default 20/30 years or so and the report concludes that
default&#xa0;
default“First, family relationships affect women’s academic careers more than men’s. Academic women typically have a spouse employed fu
defaultll time, and women with children are less likely to enter the tenure track than men
default”
default 
default3.6 A
defaultcademic careers frequently require people to move across countries or continents, and women, who are more likely to be in dual career couples, are therefore more lik
defaultely to be penalised by this, as they are statistically more likely to be earning less than their male counterpart and may also have additional childcare responsibilities. If couples wish to stay together geographically, it is statistically more likely that
default the women’s career will suffer, rather than the man’s.
default3.7 
defaultThere is evidence in an u
defaultnconscious bias in job promotion/hiring. A study in PNAS (Moss Racusin et al., 2012, 
defaulthttp://www.pnas.org/content/early/2012/09/14/1211286109#aff-1
default) showed that both men and women research scientists showed bias in favouring male applications over female 
defaultones (only name changed). The sexism exhibited was unconscious, as scientists would 
defaultgive other reasoning for their decision. We need more awareness of this, so that a conscious effort can be made to overcome any such bias; obviously there are academics who would want to change this, if only they knew they were doing it!
default3.8 
defaultWomen often un
defaultdervalue their ability and their academic potential.  It is common to hear from women with an academic background that they didn’t feel they were ‘good’ at it.
default3.9 
defaultAcademia still suffers from an image problem – young, female graduates do not perceive acade
defaultmia as a profession.  It continues to be seen as a continuation of the student lifestyle, descending into the wearing of knitted tank tops and an ever diminishing range of focus.
default 
default3.10 
defaultFinally, there were those members who simply chose to leave academia fo
