default5. What should universities and the higher education sector do to retain women graduates and PhD students in academic careers? Are there examples of good practice?
default5.1 
defaultUniversities need to demonstrate that they do not discriminate against women who want both a career and a family.  The men in these professions tend to have both, so women should be afforded the same opportunity.  
defaultA zero tolerance policy of sexism 
defaultshould be instigated and well publicised within academic centres.
default5.2 
defaultAnti-sexism training/guidance should be conducted/issued amongst the (predominantly male) professors in the position of supervising female students. 
defaultAwareness of promotion/hiring bias sh
defaultould also be considered. 
defaultFemale professors should be encouraged to act as role models for women entering academia, and actively support other women.
default5.3 
defaultInstitutions should give greater precedence to the work of women academics, championing contributions f
defaultrom the early phases of academia, and providing the opportunity for female academics to discuss and raise issues they face on an annual basis with the board of directors.
default Women should be directly encouraged to apply for more senior roles within institution
defaults.  Institutions should ensure that women are directly targeted for internal vacancies.
default5.4 
defaultA team oriented approach should be encouraged in order to eliminate aggressive competition amongst research staff.
default5.5 
defaultGood mentoring through the PhD (in addition t
defaulto academic supervision) would be a key way to improve retention of women, as whether an individual has a mentor dictates likelihood of success in science
default.
default 
defaultThis helps su
defaultpport young women in the field and helps to give incentive to their own research. One ma
defaultjor incentive is for people to understand the job prospects in their chosen field, and having good mentoring is very important in this.
default5.6 
defaultProvision of cost-effective childcare for PhD students and scientists, as well as enforcing provision of flexible wo
defaultrking. Currently it seems to be that a student or early scientist’s working arrangements are dictated mostly by their direct supervisor. If a supervisor is not understanding with regards to the extra commitments that family brings, this may well discourage
default w
defaultomen from staying in the field.
default 
default&#xa0;
default6. What role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers?
default6.1 
defaultSpecific events to attract women into the governmental research sectors can help, where women can talk and netwo
defaultrk with other women (and men) to gain insight into working in government STEM departments. 
default6.2 
defaultProvision of facilities for cost-effective childcare and flexible working are key to enabling women to co-manage a career with family commitments. Government can play a role in helping to change attitudes towards those who have family commitments, as lack 
defaultof understanding helps force out women from the sector. 
default6.3 
defaultTo boost women numbers into the sector initially, financial incentives to have certain percentages of women at each level could be offered to STEM sectors that perform poorly currently
default6.4 
defaultMen
default ha
defaultve no idea about the type of prejudice and difficulties women in STEM
default (and other industries) face. O
defaultften men just don’t know about the issues women face having never experienced them
default and awareness raising is crucial.
default6.5 
defaultPromote more women into positions o
defaultf power and responsibility.  Seeing role models encourages women to actively advance their own careers
default. C
defaultompulsory targets of the percentage of women in senior management and on Boards (e.g. 40%)
default should be set and there needs to be recognition
default and reward 
defaulto
defaultf 
defaultwomen in successful STEM careers, e.g. Honours List
default6.6 
defaultTrain science &amp; technology teachers (especially male teachers) in high schools to be consciously gender-equal in lessons, in the way opportunities are given for girls to give oral answers to whole-c
defaultlass questions and in opportunities for girls to lead in practical sessions
default6.7 
defaultLegislation is required to ensure that women taking time out of work for child-bearing have their careers protected – we should not see childbirth as detrimental to a woman’s c
defaultareer but be thankful 
defaultthat well-educated women are willing to pursue motherhood in a society that tends to deride their choices.
default6.8 
defaultFree, universal childcare should be reinstated.
default6.9 
defaultIn recruitment, where many male applicants are received and few women 
defaultper vacancy, there should be a legal obligation on the employer to offer appropriate support (such as additional training) that would bring a female candidate to the required level of competence, in order to avoid female candidates dropping out of the proc
defaultess where levels of experience resulting from career breaks for family reasons look reduced in comparison with male applicants. Similarly, women who reach the shortlist for a vacancy should be entitled to a trial period in the role, rather than ejected on 
defaultthe grounds that experience is reduced in comparison to male applicants.
default6.10 
defaultRetention of women in STEM careers, both academic and industrial, will fall as a result of increased university fees at BSc level.  Women may not see a return on their investment in university education if they choose to pursue a career in academic STEM an
defaultd a family, or re-enter academic STEM after a period in industry or the public sector. A reduction in fees, or a bonus/tax break in future for women who return to STEM careers, should therefore be considered as a form of repatriation for women entering STE
defaultM and taking on this amount risk. 
